results.name: Unitary sociable numbers of order 4.
comment: Is this a duplicate of A098188? - _R. J. Mathar_, Oct 04 2018
Note that the first 4 terms and the next 4 terms form two sociable groups. But then the 8 next terms belong to two distinct sociable groups. Whereas in A098188, the integers are grouped by cycle.
link: J. O. M. Pedersen, Known Unitary Sociable Numbers of order four [Via Internet Archive Wayback-Machine]
J. O. M. Pedersen, Order 4 cycles, 2007.
Eric Weisstein's World of Mathematics, Unitary Sociable Numbers
